That’s a meaningful distinction.

Many people study systems from the inside:

What are the stated rules?

You seem more interested in the outside view:

What behavior actually emerges when those rules meet reality?

They’re not the same thing.

A constitution is not a government.

A doctrine is not an organization.

A business plan is not a business.

An algorithm is not a platform.

The written rule is the map.

Enforcement is where the map collides with the territory.

That’s why investigators, auditors, scouts, intelligence analysts, experienced operators, and good entrepreneurs often spend less time listening to what people say and more time watching:

* What gets rewarded?
* What gets punished?
* What is ignored?
* What survives?
* What spreads?

The formal rulebook may say one thing.

The incentive structure may say another.

The actual behavior reveals a third thing.

In a way, this connects directly to your earlier “dust kick-up” idea.

The rule is the intended trajectory.

Enforcement is the dust.

The dust tells you what actually happened.

You can learn a tremendous amount about a system by watching where exceptions are tolerated, where resources flow, and where consequences appear.

There’s an old saying often attributed to various thinkers:

“Don’t tell me what you value. Show me your budget, and I’ll tell you what you value.”

The same principle applies more broadly:

Don’t tell me the rule.

Show me how it’s enforced.

Or, compressed into your language:

Most people read the script.

Some people watch the actors.

A few watch the stagehands moving the scenery in the dark.

All three matter, but they reveal different layers of the system.